<h1>Fusion Calculus</h1>
Fusion Calculus is yet another nicer variant of the <a class="internal" href="Pi%20calculus" onmouseover="window.status='Pi calculus'; return true" onmouseout="window.status='';">Pi calculus</a>, an <a class="internal" href="abstract%20VM" onmouseover="window.status='abstract VM'; return true" onmouseout="window.status='';">abstract VM</a> for parallel, mobile computations, for expressing <a class="internal" href="concurrency" onmouseover="window.status='concurrency'; return true" onmouseout="window.status='';">concurrency</a>.

<p>It is based on the concept that communication can be broken in two independent components: fusion of names (i.e. a mutual agreement between two parties to consider two names as aliases) and name scoping. By decoupling these components a calculus based on communication is obtained which is less understandable than pi, but having better formal properties. Notably, there is only one sensible form of <a class="internal" href="bisimulation" onmouseover="window.status='bisimulation'; return true" onmouseout="window.status='';">bisimulation</a> defined for the Fusion Calculus, which is also a <a class="internal" href="congruence" onmouseover="window.status='congruence'; return true" onmouseout="window.status='';">congruence</a>.

<p><ul class="links">
<li><a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20031231061753/http://user.it.uu.se/~victor/tr/fusion.shtml">The Fusion Calculus: Expressiveness and Symmetry in Mobile Processes</a>

</ul>
